{"id":"1406.6675","submitter":"Volodymyr Ihnatovych","authors":"V. Ihnatovych","title":"Philosophical roots of the \"eternal\" questions in the XX-century\n  theoretical physics","comments":"9 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.hist-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The evolution of theoretical physics in the XX century differs significantly\nfrom that in XVII-XIX centuries. While continuous progress is observed for\ntheoretical physics in XVII-XIX centuries, modern physics contains many\nquestions that have not been resolved despite many decades of discussion. Based\nupon the analysis of works by the founders of the XX-century physics, the\nconclusion is made that the roots of the \"eternal\" questions by the XX-century\ntheoretical physics lie in the philosophy used by its founders. The conclusion\nis made about the need to use the ideas of philosophy that guided C. Huygens,\nI. Newton, W. Thomson (Lord Kelvin), J. K. Maxwell, and the other great\nphysicists of the XVII-XIX centuries, in all areas of theoretical physics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 27 May 2014 20:52:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-06-26"}
